05334nam a22008295i 9783110457643DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2016    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104576437 a10.1515/97831104576432doi  a(DE-B1597)460696  a(OCoLC)979690608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPN51 7aPOL0330002bisacsh 7aSOC0000002bisacsh 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a809.91 aBiti, Vladimir, eauthor.10aTracing Global Democracy :bLiterature, Theory, and the Politics of Trauma /cVladimir Biti. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (403 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture & Conflict ;v700tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Cosmopolitan Axis: Agencies and/or Enablers -- tPart I: Toward a Global Community: The Emergence of the Modern Idea of Literature -- t1. The Divided Legacy of the Republic of Letters: Emancipation and Trauma -- t2. The Fissured Identity of Literature: National Universalism and/or Cosmopolitan Nationalism -- t3. The Janus Face of Literary Bildung: Education and/or Self-Formation? -- t4. Who Voices Universal History? Kant's "Mankind" and/or Herder's "Nature" -- t5. Who Worlds the Literature? Goethe's Weltliteratur and Globalization -- tPart II: An Observer under Observation: The Cosmopolitan Legacy of Modern Theory -- t6. Interiorizing the Exteriority: The Cosmopolitan Authorization of the Theoretical Truth -- t7. The Narrative of Permanent Displacement: Early German Romanticism and Its Theoretical Afterlife -- t8. The Oppositional Literary Transcendental: The Russian Formalist Rewriting of Early Romanticist Cosmopolitanism -- t9. The All-Devouring Modern Mind: Bakhtin's Cosmopolitan Self -- t10. Countering the Empirical Evidence: From Immigrant Cosmopolitanism to a Cosmopolitanism of the Disregarded -- t11. Political and/or Literary Community: From Class to Messianic Cosmopolitanism -- t12. Literature as Deterritorialization: New Vistas for Democracy? -- tEpilogue: The Practice of Recommencing: Toward a Cosmopolitanism of the Dispossessed Belonging -- tReferences -- tIndex  aFocused on the recently hotly debated topic at the crossroads of various human and social sciences, this book investigates the emergence of the cosmopolitan idea of literature and its impact on the reconfiguration of the European and non-European political spaces. The birthplace of this idea is its designers' traumatic experience as induced by the disconcerting condition of their abode.The thesis is that the eighteenth and nineteenth century's cosmopolitan projects that grow out of such deep frustrations trace the twentieth century's global democracy. This hidden origin of cosmopolitan projects dismantles the usual European representation of modernization as universal progress as myopic. Rather than being a generous action of prominent subjects such as Voltaire, Kant, and Goethe, or Bakhtin, Derrida and Deleuze, cosmopolitanism is an enforced reaction of the instances dispossessed by injury that search for the ways of healing it. Yet as soon as their remedy establishes itself as the ground for universal reconciliation, it risks suppressing other's trauma, i.e. turns from politics into a police. Articulating the author's position in the recent debates on the structure of democracy, the epilogue suggests an alternative strategy.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aLiterature and society. 0aTrauma. 4aLiterature, democracy, cosmopolitanism, trauma. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-D